<p>
When a @Vte{{}}@HI{{iru}} verb form indicating a situation has arisen as a result of the <em>completion</em> of an action is used to modify a noun,
the form @Vta{{}} can be used instead.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@FG{{@KJ{{rice*field^in}}:tanaka}}sanha@FG{{@KJ{{eyeball^mirror}}:megane}}wokaketeimasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Mr. Tanaka is wearing spectacles.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
The sentence can be rewritten using @Vta{{}} instead.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{eyeball^mirror}}wokake@EM{{ta}}@FG{{@KJ{{rice*field^in}}:tanaka}}san'}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Mr. Tanaka, who is wearing spectacles
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
However, when the same transformation is applied in the case of a verb indicating an ongoing action, the meaning changes.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@FG{{@KJ{{east^capital}}:toukyou}}@FG{{@KJ{{electricity^spirit}}:denki}}de@FG{{@KJ{{work}}:hatara}}iteiru@FG{{@KJ{{friend^accomplished}}:tomodachi}}}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      My friend, who works at Tokyo Electric
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
The @Vta{{}} form of the sentence has a slightly different meaning.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@FG{{@KJ{{east^capital}}:toukyou}}@FG{{@KJ{{electricity^spirit}}:denki}}de@FG{{@KJ{{work}}:hatara}}i@EM{{ta}}@FG{{@KJ{{friend^accomplished}}:tomodachi}}}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      My friend, who worked at Tokyo Electric
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

